article.headline: Ohlde scores 16 of 24 points in first half
article.linkText: Ohlde's 24 points lift Kansas State over Cowgirls
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Oklahoma State tried just about every
defensive scheme imaginable against Kansas State in the first half.

	   It worked -- on everyone but Nicole Ohlde.

	   Ohlde scored 16 of her 24 points in the first half, and grabbed
12 rebounds as fifth-ranked Kansas State recovered from a poor
offensive performance in the opening half and beat Oklahoma State
64-46 Saturday night.

	   "Ohlde was a huge presence on the inside,'' Kansas State
forward Kendra Wecker said.

	   The Wildcats (23-2, 10-1 Big 12) overcame poor shooting from
every other Wildcat in the first half to beat Oklahoma State (5-17,
1-10) for the first time in the last four meetings between the
teams. Kansas State last beat the Cowgirls on Feb. 9, 2000.

	   Wecker finished with 17 points despite shooting 6-of-19. Amy
Dutmer had 11 rebounds for the Wildcats. Trisha Skibbe led the
Cowgirls with 18 points and 12 rebounds and Shelby Hutchens scored 10.

	   Kansas State led only 31-30 at halftime, but scored 11 straight
points to start the second half and the Cowgirls never recovered.

	   "It was absolutely a difference of night and day between the
two halves,'' Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said. "The first
half was a real struggle. As we missed more and more, we tried to
force more and more.''

	   The Wildcats were 5-of-20 from the field with 6:35 left in the
first half, but shot 51 percent after that to win their 19th
straight at home.

	   Oklahoma State, which committed 17 turnovers, lost its eighth
straight.

	   "To be within one at halftime was quite an accomplishment for
our kids,'' Oklahoma State coach Julie Goodenough said. "Late in
the game, we were still within single digits. But we missed 3s and
they knocked them down.''

	   With Wecker on the bench with two fouls, the Wildcats missed
their first eight shots and the Cowgirls quickly took an 8-0 lead
to start the game. Oklahoma State led by as many as 13 before the
Wildcats settled down.

	   Ohlde's layup with 7:05 left sparked a 7-0 run that cut the lead
to five with five minutes left in the half. The Wildcats took their
first lead of the game when Ohlde made a free throw with 6.4
seconds left in the half. Kansas State never trailed after that.

	   "We're finding a way to compete through 40 minutes,'' Patterson
said. "That's what's important.''
